Here's a simple JavaScript program that allows users to draw on an HTML5 canvas:

```javascript
// Get the canvas element
var canvas = document.getElementById('canvas');
var ctx = canvas.getContext('2d');

// Set the canvas dimensions
canvas.width = 400;
canvas.height = 400;

// Set the drawing variables
var drawing = false;
var lastX, lastY;

// Add event listeners for mouse events
canvas.addEventListener('mousedown', function(event) {
    drawing = true;
    lastX = event.clientX;
    lastY = event.clientY;
});

canvas.addEventListener('mousemove', function(event) {
    if (drawing) {
        ctx.beginPath();
        ctx.moveTo(lastX, lastY);
        ctx.lineTo(event.clientX, event.clientY);
        ctx.stroke();
        lastX = event.clientX;
        lastY = event.clientY;
    }
});

canvas.addEventListener('mouseup', function(event) {
    drawing = false;
});
```

This program creates a canvas element and sets its dimensions to 400x400 pixels. It then sets up event listeners for mouse events, including mousedown, mousemove, and mouseup. When the user clicks and drags the mouse, the program draws a line on the canvas from the last known position to the current position. When the user releases the mouse button, the drawing stops.

To use this program, simply add the following HTML code to your page:

```html
<canvas id="canvas"></canvas>
```

This will create a canvas element with the ID "canvas" and add the JavaScript program to it. You can then use the canvas element to draw on the page.

